So far, we’ve covered basic conditionals like `if` and `if-else`.

In C programming, the `if-else if` structure is used when you need to check multiple conditions and execute the corresponding block of code for the first true condition. It is particularly useful for checking ranges or multiple mutually exclusive options.

**Syntax:**

```c
if (condition1) {
    // Executes if condition1 is true
} else if (condition2) {
    // Executes if condition2 is true
} else {
    // Executes if none of the above conditions are true
}
```

---

**Example:**

```c
#include

int main() {
    // Declare and initialize age
    int age = 45;

    // Check age group
    if (age >= 60) {
        printf("Senior Citizen\n");  // Age is 60 or above
    }
    // Check if the person is an adult but not a senior
    else if (age >= 18) {
        printf("Adult\n");  // Age is between 18 and 59
    }
    // If age is less than 18
    else {
        printf("Minor\n");  // Age is below 18
    }

    return 0;
}
```

**Expected Output:**

```default
Adult
```

